WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
We're going to be talking about importing data into R.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:07.000
And with that, these are the topics that I want to cover.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:13.000
I want to start with a brief overview of why data is important and importing it into R.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:19.000
And then we're going to, you know, take a look into different types of data that are interesting to import.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.000
We're going to start with tabular data.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:31.000
This is pretty much the file that you would be used to as importing a CSV, you know, text, flat text files, Excel files, SAS, SPSS.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:38.000
We're going to take a look at hierarchical data, which, you know, is pretty common on the web with things like HTML, JSON, and XML.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Afterwards, we're going to jump to relational data, as in relational databases.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:49.000
And finally, I want to give a tease on how to import data from distributed systems.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:56.000
You know, the more common term here is big data, so we're going to do a quick demo for each of these categories.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
And afterwards, we're going to have a session of questions.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:03.000
All right, well, let's get started with the overview.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.000
And this is a diagram that shows how the typical data science project looks like.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:16.000
It came from the R4DataScience book, which is currently on pre-sale, I believe, but all the content is available online.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:23.000
And, you know, what this diagram tells us is basically, you know, the way that I want to see it is that data importing is pretty important.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
You really can't have data science if you don't have data.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:34.000
And this is your very first step before you actually clean up the data and start understanding it and, you know, before you communicate.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.000
So definitely relevant.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:43.000
And also the caveat is that there are so many sources that we can use to import data from that this webinar is only, you know,

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
touch the surface of a lot of different concepts that we can use to import data.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:55.000
There's going to be more webinars that you can attend and more resources that we can point you to in order to import data into R.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:58.000
But we're going to cover the main ones.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:03.000
So with that, let's start with importing tabular data.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:11.000
And this might be obvious to a lot of you, but it's good to take a step back and just think about what is tabular data.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
A lot of times we think that we have tabular data, but we might not.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And the structure is very simple.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:20.000
We have a set of variables, right?

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Each variable is represented in the column and each row represents an observation.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Obviously, each cell contains values and we want these values per column to be homogeneous, right?

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:37.000
We want them to have the same type.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.000
You know, we want to have interiors in each column, if that's an interior column, et cetera.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:49.000
So still, it's obvious, but it's good that while you're looking into importing data, you have this notion of how a good tabular data source looks like.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:58.000
And if it doesn't look like this, you might be looking at a different type of data and you might need to use different tools.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:06.000
So we're going to be covering a couple of the basic file types that you might be interested in importing.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And for that, I'm going to switch to RStudio to run a couple demos.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:17.000
So let's go here.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:26.000
And we have RStudio and we're going to start by importing a CSV file.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And the package that we recommend using for importing CSVs and general flat files is read CSV.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.000
So you can run this comment.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:43.000
In the most simple case, you only need a path to your file and then you would be able to view the contents.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:51.000
This file is about two megabytes and we can load it all and have a sense of how it looks like.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:58.000
We have a couple other options to import tabular data.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.000
For Excel files, we recommend the read Excel package.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.000
And again, they function in a very similar way.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:16.000
So we can run that with a single parameter, which is just the path to the file and get the results.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:22.000
And we have a couple other ones here which come from a statistical software, just executing the three of them at the same time.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:29.000
And we can take a look at what this data source contains.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:37.000
So the simple use cases are very easy to get started with.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:46.000
There's just mostly a path to the file and each package will try to do inference on the columns and data that is being imported.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:56.000
However, the feature that I want to show is a new improvement that we have in RStudio to make our life easier while importing these data sources.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And the reason why this is interesting is that not all the time is as easy as just importing a file.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Sometimes we want to change column names, sometimes we want to change some of the settings that each package provides to us.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:17.000
So here, if you were to click on RStudio under the import data set comment, you're going to get a new menu.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
Now there is a caveat here.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:23.000
This is a pretty new feature, so it's not on the last release of RStudio.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
You would have to download the preview version of RStudio.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:34.000
Now if you're watching this webinar later on, it's most likely going to be the case that it's part of the latest version of RStudio.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:44.000
But for now, the easiest thing to do if you're interested in using this feature is to download the preview by searching in your favorite engine RStudio preview and downloading that.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
So you know that you have this feature if you have a menu that looks like this.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And to import a CSV, all you need to do is click on import CSV.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And what you would get is a text box with the file name and file path that you want to use to import data.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:08.000
This file path supports local sources, meaning that they live on your local computer.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:13.000
But you can also point this to a URL and import data directly from the web.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
So let's do this.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:21.000
And as you can see here, we have some of the sources from this tutorial that you're going to be able to access.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
And we can pick a CSV file.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:29.000
So when we open the CSV file, we're actually not importing it into R yet.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:34.000
What we're doing for you is we're giving you a preview of how the data looks like.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
So you can see here that you have 50 entries.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:42.000
The file is actually longer, but we're giving you a preview of how this looks like.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.000
And you have a lot of options to configure how this data should be imported.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:53.000
So for instance, a lot of data sources don't come with the first header as names of the columns.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:01.000
So you can toggle that really fast and create an extra one, create an extra row for the headers.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:09.000
And also what is good to see is that we're generating also a preview of the code that you would get to import this data.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
So here the parameter that we're changing is column names.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:19.000
So you can also use this dialog as a great way to just learn more about RADAR and the parameters that it supports.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:27.000
You can change if you were to be importing a different delimited file,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:34.000
and you have a tab delimited file or just delimited by white spaces, you can also change those settings here.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:42.000
One of the interesting ones that it's very easy to do in this dialog is to choose columns or change their data type.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:51.000
So for instance, at times you would see that RADAR is pretty intelligent on choosing which is the column type that it's importing.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.000
So in this case, it thinks that this ID, it's an integer, which is the case.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:59.000
So that's a good data type to use to import this data.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:09.000
But if you look at the date on this priority date column, you'll see that it's being imported by default as character,

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
and that might not be what you want.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:15.000
So very easily you can say change to a date.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.000
You can specify the formatting string to parse this and accept the change.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:25.000
And as you can see, it has already taken place, and this column is going to be imported as a date column.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
You can also preview the code the same way.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:41.000
We're basically creating a data import statement on RADAR to specify the column priority date as a date with a specific format type.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:51.000
The other good feature that I personally use a lot is to say you can select columns to skip or to only import.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:57.000
So sometimes we have a very large CSV file, and we're really only interested in three or four columns.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:03.000
So you can use also READSR functionality to select only the column that you want to import.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:09.000
So for this case, we're looking at government data.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:16.000
There's different application names each with a date, and this might be all the information that I want.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:25.000
So once you have a good preview of how the data looks like, you can import that into R very easily.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.000
So this is how it looks like at this point.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:33.000
This is a data table that you can use to further do analysis on R.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:39.000
In a similar way, we can import data directly from Excel.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:47.000
You want to select XLSX files.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:51.000
The functionality is similar but a bit different.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:10:02.000
One of the most used features in this dialog while importing data from Excel is to select the sheet on the source spreadsheet that you're interested in.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:08.000
So in this case, we only have one, but if you were to have multiple ones, you would be able to select the specific sheet that is interesting to you.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:21.000
And in a similar way, you can change some of the data types and skip some of the columns that might not be very interesting for your data analysis.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:27.000
So in this case, this might just be all we want in order to import this data set,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:38.000
and you can just go ahead and import it and have a data frame built for you on R to continue your analysis.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:48.000
Let's take a quick look at one more code path to get your data imported.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:55.000
In this case, we'll try to import a sub-file.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
Here we have some data set.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:11.000
Again, some of the things that you could also do would be to change the data frame name.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
So maybe here we can say this data.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:20.000
And you would see that this updates real-time and you get a preview of how that import is going to look like.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:31.000
And again, you just need to click import and you would get a data frame with that functionality baked into the read sub-comment.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
So this is pretty much it.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:38.000
I really encourage everyone just to take a quick look and play with the different parameters.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:44.000
It's a great way to learn about the community packages through the IDE.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:53.000
I'm going to go back to the presentation and just quickly cover what we just demoed.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
So again, this feature is only available on RStudio Preview for now.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:02.000
So if you're interested in playing with this, you need to download RStudio Preview.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:07.000
And the main entry point is through the environment tab under import data set.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:16.000
You can select different sources and then you would get this dialog to do a preview, in-place preview of your data before importing.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:22.000
There's definitely, again, we're covering just the surface on how to import tabular data.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:29.000
There's more resources that Bill pointed to and there's definitely more upcoming webinars if you're also interested in further topics.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:37.000
Sorry, with that, we're going to take a look at another class of data which doesn't fit well with tabular data.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
And this is called hierarchical data.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So just a quick review of what is hierarchical data.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:52.000
And if you look at Wikipedia, it would say something like this, a data model in which the data is organized into a tree-like structure.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:59.000
In this particular representation that we have on this slide, you can look at it as an inverted tree, right?

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Where, you know, there's a model and that model starts with a root which, you know, has this label called pavement improvements.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:16.000
And each of the different branches has, you know, a different data value.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:21.000
So whenever you see branches, you know, nested branching on a data set, it's probably not tabular data.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
It's probably hierarchical data.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
I need to use a different set of tools to import that data.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:33.000
Now the interesting thing about hierarchical data is that it's really everywhere and that's the interesting part.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:42.000
So one of the common file types is what we call XML, which stands for Extensible Markup Language.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
It looks like the top left block that we have on this slide.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:50.000
And, you know, in this case, we only have one level.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
It's a simple node from someone to someone.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.000
But we could have nested levels where, you know, like the structure is more complicated.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:03.000
Interestingly, there is a very strong relationship between XML and HTML.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And HTML is basically everywhere, right?

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:13.000
So whenever you look at a web page and you look at the sources, you're going to see that it follows this tree-like structure

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:20.000
when the document is defined as an HTML document and then there's a head that describes, you know, things like the title on the page

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
and also a body where it describes the actual values.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And in a similar way, sometimes where you're importing data not necessarily from a web page but from a web service or from a web API,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:37.000
the type of data that you would usually get is called JSON, which stands for JavaScript Notation.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.000
We have a sample on the bottom left of this slide.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
And it can also be nested.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And it's very common, you know, if you were to import data from Yelp or some of the web services that are out there,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:55.000
you would get a nested structure that describes the request that you're performing.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:01.000
And tabular, importing this as a tabular data structure wouldn't fit very well here.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:08.000
So let's take a quick look at a demo that we have for importing tabular data.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:19.000
This should be on the hierarchical data.r file on the resources that we're providing on this webinar.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:24.000
And we're going to start by importing data as JSON, right?

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
So this one has multiple levels.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:33.000
So once the data is imported, we're going to take the first element of the first branch,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.000
and then we're going to take the first element of the next branch on that element.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
So I'm going to run that.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
And what you can see is that we're getting a nested list of data.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:51.000
And, you know, you would use different tools to clean this further up.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
You can do something very similar by importing XML data.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:16:01.000
So in this case, the way that you access each node from this branch would be with XML children.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
So once you import your data, let's import it first.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
Now it's on this node.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:15.000
And once you want to access a specific data source on this nested structure,

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:19.000
you would access it by going first to the first children in this case,

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:23.000
and then getting the children of that particular node.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:31.000
Now a more interesting use case is what happens when, you know, you want to import data from the web.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:38.000
And we just mentioned that HTML is another type of hierarchical data.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.000
And so let's look at the more interesting example here.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:47.000
So here we're looking at a Wikipedia page, List of Countries and Dependencies by Population.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
And obviously, you know, this is all text.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:54.000
But there is a table that looks very interesting.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:17:01.000
And in this case, Wikipedia doesn't have, like, a download, you know, data, you know, feature or anything.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
But this might be something that you want to import directly into R.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:09.000
And there's going to be an upcoming webinar on just how to do, you know, web scraping.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:13.000
But I want to give you, you know, like a quick overview of how you would do this, right?

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
So you have a URL.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
So you can copy that URL.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:22.000
And you would want to use, in this case, a different package called Arvest.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:29.000
And you would call in a similar way that you read XML or JSON, you would say read HTML.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:33.000
And what this would do is would read the entire web page as HTML.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
So now it's parsed.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:38.000
It's in a hierarchical format.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:42.000
Still not very usable at this point because it's basically the whole web page.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:45.000
What you could do is you could look at a very specific element.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:54.000
So you can, if you were to look here at the source of this page, you would see that there is a table element on this table.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:02.000
And you could address that specific element by using what is called an XPath to the element.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
So let's run that.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
And that's going to give you that particular element.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:11.000
And then finally, you can use one function from the Arvest package, which is very useful,

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:18.000
which is saying, well, load this table as an HTML table from an HTML table.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:22.000
So let's execute this statement.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:28.000
And what you can see is that, you know, it starts with China and, you know, biggest population June 22nd,

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:35.000
which, you know, like it's the first row that you would get on your web page.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:38.000
And again, there's going to be an upcoming webinar for this.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:43.000
This is just scratching the surface of what you can do by scraping data from the web.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:50.000
But it's really interesting and certainly very, very helpful.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:19:03.000
All right, with that, I'm going to come back and we're going to explore another category on the data sources that you might want to import into R.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:04.000
Let's see.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:09.000
So we look at this couple of these examples with XML, Arvest and JSON.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:14.000
And now we're going to look at importing relational data.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:22.000
And again, I wanted to spend a little bit of time just kind of like understanding what's the difference between hierarchical data and relational data.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:28.000
So in hierarchical data, as we talk about, we're always talking about branching in relational data.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:33.000
What we're talking about is relationships between data.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.000
Right.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:41.000
In Wikipedia, you could find a quote that reads that data is represented in terms of tuples and group it into relations.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:50.000
And tuples is nothing more than a set of columns that are related with each other.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.000
But then we can also have relationships between them.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:54.000
Right.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:05.000
So, for instance, some of the things that wouldn't be supported in a hierarchical structure would be, for instance, when you have a list of when your company has a list of customers.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:08.000
So that relationship could be hierarchical.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:29.000
But the fact that also customers could have relationships with their favorite brands in there that are companies, you know, it's it's kind of like a loop that goes from customers to companies and from companies to customer that you would model with a with a relational looking data structure.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:30.000
So. All right.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:31.000
So this is how it looks like.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:34.000
And the best representation of this is a database.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:35.000
Right.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:38.000
I'm sure a lot of you would be familiar with databases.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:44.000
And the interesting thing to mention here is that there's obviously a lot of database software out there.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:51.000
The table on the right shows some of the different software providers of database software.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:54.000
And there's definitely there's just definitely a lot of them.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:19.000
So what you really want to do, since you know, like this is this can get chaotic pretty fast, is you want to use a package that can wrap that complexity around connecting to each of the different data sources with something that it's usually called a driver, which is basically a translator between what you want to do with your database and the actual information in the database.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:22.000
And yeah.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:26.000
And for that, a great package to work with these is called DBI.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.000
And DBI would allow you to connect to multiple data sources.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:33.000
And we're going to see a couple examples of these.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:38.000
So let me switch to back to our demo.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:41.000
And.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:44.000
That would be the third example on the webinar.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:53.000
And one of the things that you want to do is obviously first install the DBI package, and then you would have to find which is the correct backend.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:57.000
And by backend, I just mean database that you need to connect to.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:01.000
There's definitely different backends that you could use.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:05.000
Some of them are what we call generic and some of them are specialized.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:12.000
So for instance, in this case, if you were to connect to Postgres, you would have to run a statement that looks like this, DB connect.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:16.000
And then you specify the Postgres driver.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:23.000
The best thing to do is to use the driver that is specific to the database that you're connecting to.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:26.000
And mostly, mostly because this is usually a performance game.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:33.000
Usually most of the features are implemented on the on the specific backend that you're connecting to.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:43.000
If for some reason you don't find a driver to your specific database, what you can do is use one of the generic ones like our ODBC and our JDBC.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:54.000
And those are standard connections to databases that usually need a little bit more of configuration that we're not doing this this tutorial.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:59.000
But it would allow you to connect in a generic way to each of the databases.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:06.000
Another example, very, very used database software is the driver for MySQL.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:15.000
And as you can see, you know, it's basically the same statement that you would execute for connecting to Postgres you would use to connect to MySQL.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:18.000
And that's the point of this package.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:29.000
The DBI package is trying to abstract away the complexities of dealing with multiple backends into a single package with very few configuration steps.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:36.000
So for our for our example, during this webinar, what we're going to do is we're going to connect to SQLite.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:48.000
SQLite is also a database software that allows, it's very easy to allow you to connect in local settings like the one I'm using.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:24:01.000
In fact, in this case, I'm pointing this database to be stored in the database.sqlite file that you could see on the tutorial, sorry, webinar resources.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:05.000
So here you can see there is a database SQLite file.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:11.000
And all you have to do is connect to it and it's going to create a database connection to that particular data set.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:22.000
The first step that you probably want to do while connecting to a database is just to list the tables and to kind of like understand what types of tables you have in this database.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:24.000
In this case, it's a very simple database.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:28.000
It has only one table that I created myself.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:40.000
And then in order to retrieve data from a database, you would want to say dbquery and execute a query.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:42.000
And this is a SQL query.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:46.000
There's a lot of references on the web on how to craft queries.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:53.000
There's also packages that we recommend using like the plier that will remove the need to use specific SQL queries.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:25:01.000
But today we're talking about importing data, so we're not going to touch on other more advanced ways of transforming and manipulating data.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:12.000
But once you have your data locally, you can obviously look at the result sets.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:23.000
You can do the same type of processing that you would do with any other data frame in the same way that we imported hierarchical data and in the same way that we imported tabular data.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:31.000
Finally, one last step but not less important is to disconnect from the database.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:34.000
It's just a polite thing to do.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:41.000
Otherwise, the data source might keep resources running and it could degrade performance.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:47.000
So just a single step code to disconnect away from the database.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:56.000
If you were to use, again, one of these commands, it wouldn't obviously work because while dealing with databases, the first step that you want to do is disconnect.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:00.000
So again, a quick recap, we use the DBI driver.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:05.000
And in order to connect to the particular database of your interest, you want to use a driver.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:10.000
There's different types of drivers, much more than these three that I'm presenting here.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:25.000
And then you would want to manipulate and extract data using SQL-like statements or higher-level packages like Deployer that would allow you to do this without even selecting, having to craft your own SQL statements.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.000
Perfect.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:30.000
So let's go to the last topic here.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:41.000
And the last topic that we want to cover is importing data from distributed sources.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.000
And what does this mean?

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:46.000
So we talk about tabular.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:49.000
We talk about hierarchical and relational.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:54.000
And this is a little bit of a similar concept, but the scope is different, right?

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:04.000
So in a lot of cases, you know, when dealing with CSV files, you can have the CSV files on your local machine because they just feed into memory and that's all good.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:12.000
And it's usually, you know, it's usually okay to just import a CSV file directly from your local machine.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:17.000
Sometimes as the data grows, data gets ported into a relational model.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:21.000
And you can import this data with tools like DBI, as we saw in the demo.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:31.000
But there's also cases where the data just doesn't even fit on or is not advised to be feeding to a database relational model.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:41.000
So in these cases, we're talking of what is also known as big data, where the data just doesn't feed into a single machine or even a few machines.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:47.000
You know, like databases, it's not uncommon to have like, you know, under replicated database with three or four machines.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:50.000
But sometimes data doesn't even feed on those systems.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:56.000
And you need like several hundreds or several thousands or even tens of thousands of nodes.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:03.000
By node, I mean what we're representing on top of these on the top of the slide.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.000
By nodes, I mean just computers.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:14.000
So when data doesn't fit on a few computers or even a single computer, we need to introduce the concept of distributed data.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:23.000
And basically what it means is that we need to split the data into multiple different pieces in order to be able to deal with it, right?

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:31.000
So if you have like a really, really large file that doesn't fit on one machine, but only fits in like machine machines,

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:37.000
you have to distribute that file across like all those different machines and somehow work with it on R.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:42.000
So that's a bit what I want to talk about on these last conceptual data source.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:44.000
You have a lot of data.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:45.000
It's distributed data.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:55.000
And it's just not possible to deal with all the data in your machine running, you know, like a single hard drive with a few processors.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:58.000
So how does that look like?

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:09.000
So there's two approaches to tackle this problem of having too much data that doesn't fit into one machine that you can't really import into your R session.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:12.000
So the first concept is sampling.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:14.000
And this is a statistical concept.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:23.000
And the idea is that, you know, you might not be able to bring all the Twitter data into your laptop.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:26.000
That's just not feasible because it's just too much.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:28.000
But you can definitely take a subset of that data.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:35.000
So you can say, well, you know, I know that I can take all the information from all these countries.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:44.000
But I can take a few rows from each country and process that in a subsampled way on the local machine.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:45.000
So that's one way.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:50.000
And that's what we're going to explore today on the demo during this webinar.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:57.000
The second option is to say, well, I know that the data doesn't fit in this particular machine.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:13.000
So instead of running my code with a subset of data in this current machine, what I'm going to do is instead going to run my R code in distributed fashion across all the nodes and do the processing outside of this current machine.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:17.000
And that's definitely deserves a webinar by itself.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:23.000
And definitely there's interesting news coming on this topic.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:27.000
But today I want to focus on sampling.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.000
So two options.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
One is reduce the number of data that you bring down.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:38.000
And the other option is do processing of data outside of your current laptop and do it on each node.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:46.000
So let's look at how it looks to sample data for a specific data source.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
How would we bring data into R?

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:53.000
And, again, I'm not talking here about very specific technologies because there's just so many.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:56.000
I've listed some on the right side of the slide.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:59.000
We have Spark, Hadoop, Cassandra, Mesos.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
There's just a lot of technology.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:04.000
So that definitely deserves its own webinar by itself.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:11.000
But I want to at least expose ourselves during this webinar on how we would tackle this problem.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:16.000
So we're looking at the sampling approach.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:24.000
And what I'm going to do in this case, and this is, you know, unrelated in some way with R,

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:28.000
since it's going to be dependent on each system that has distributed data.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:30.000
But the approach would look a little bit like this.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
And, you know, we don't need to go into details.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:36.000
I just kind of, like, want to present how this would look like.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:42.000
And the idea is here what we're using is what is called we're getting data from Spark.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:45.000
And we're using what is called a Spark shell.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
And the approach that I want to present is pretty simple.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:52.000
So what you would do is you would find where your data is.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:58.000
Usually the data is in systems like Amazon S3 or HDFS.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:01.000
In this case, for this demo, it's just a local file.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:09.000
And then you would load that file using the distributed, you know, system.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:16.000
And that's still, you know, we're working against, you know, not R but against a distributed system.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:18.000
In this case, it's Spark.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:22.000
Then you can do, you know, you can do a couple things like just getting the number of rows.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:26.000
And here the interesting thing, you know, we are only looking at 5,000 rows.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:35.000
But in a real application scenario, this could be billions or, you know, like even hundreds or, you know,

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:42.000
it would be like a much more bigger data set that just is not feasible to bring down into your own machine.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:46.000
So what we're going to do in this case is we're going to take a sample of the data.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:54.000
And a lot of distributed systems provide functionality one way or another one to, you know, get you to extract a subset of this data.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.000
So that's exactly what we're doing.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:00.000
And then in this case, what we want to do is we just want to save the file locally.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:03.000
In Spark, this concept is called collecting the data.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:07.000
What we're going to do in this case is save it.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:13.000
And as you can see, a new file appeared here, which is the sampled subset of the data.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:17.000
And again, we didn't look at a lot of the details of how to do this,

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:21.000
mostly because it's a little bit out of the scope of how you would import data.

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:26.000
But my bigger point here is that, you know, if you were faced with this problem,

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:34.000
what you would want to do is either ask someone or yourself, try to sample down the data for this approach, for the sampling approach.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.000
So here you can see that is a CSV file.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:42.000
And we can import this CSV file using the same tools that we just learned about today.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:48.000
So let's browse for this file that just got imported today.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:52.000
It's called sampled with the same name.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:53.000
We're going to open it.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:34:00.000
And as you can see, you know, we have the data that we would expect,

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:06.000
but it's sampled to something that is manageable on our specific laptop, right?

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:14.000
So here, if I import this one, and I were to say, let's look at the number of rows from this data set,

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:20.000
you would see that it only contains a subset of the data that we imported.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:22.000
All right.

